{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12400"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12400"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.01,0.04,0.76,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49317"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4908"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42750"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49317"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department of a rural hospital with a one hour history of severe central chest pain. He describes the pain as a tight pressure and it is making him sweat and gasp for air. His medical history include hypertension, for which he takes irbesartan. He has a 25 pack-year smoking history. On examination, his blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg and pulse 110/min. An electrocardiogram is performed (Image). Oral aspirin, sublingual nitroglycerin and IV morphine is given for pain. The nearest PCI capable hospital is 2.5 hours away.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bisoprolol","Phenylephrine","Atropine","Alteplase","Rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows a sinus tachycardia with premature atrial complexes. There is significant ST elevations in the inferior leads (II, III, aVf) consistent with an acute inferior myocardial infarction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteplase\u003C/strong\u003E is a thrombolytic agent that can help dissolve the blood clot that is blocking the blood flow to the heart muscle. Thrombolytics are used to treat an AMI where primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) cannot be performed within 120 minutes of initial medical contact which is typically considered the gold-standard for STEMI management in Australia. Given this patient presented to a hospital 2.5 hours from a PCI capable facility, thrombolysis should be initiated immediately. By dissolving the clot and restoring blood flow to the heart, they can prevent further damage to the heart muscle. This can reduce the risk of complications such as heart failure, arrhythmia and death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker that is commonly used in the management of hypertension and heart failure, and it is often used after an acute myocardial infarction to reduce the risk of recurrent events. However, in this acute setting, the patient is experiencing ongoing chest pain and ST-segment elevation on the electrocardiogram, suggesting an active AMI. While beta-blockers are generally helpful in the management of myocardial infarction, they are not the appropriate initial therapy in this case because they can worsen the patient\u0027s heart failure (if any) by further decreasing blood flow to the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenylephrine\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective \u03b11-adrenergic receptor agonist used in the management of hypotension due to shock by causing vasoconstriction. In this case there is no indication for administration of this medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine\u003C/strong\u003E is a medication that can be used to increase heart rate in patients with bradycardia through its anticholinergic mechanism of action. However, the patient in this case has a fast heart rate and atropine would not be helpful in this situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the acute setting of an AMI because it is primarily an anticoagulant, while the acute treatment of AMI focuses on rapidly restoring blood flow through thrombolytic therapy or mechanical interventions like PCI. Anticoagulants like rivaroxaban are more commonly used for long-term prevention of thromboembolic events rather than immediate clot dissolution. Additionally, the use of rivaroxaban in the acute phase may increase the risk of bleeding complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent studies suggest that nitroglycerin (GTN) may be safely administered in cases of inferior STEMI, including those with right ventricular involvement, under specific conditions. A significant study found that the incidence of hypotension following GTN administration was not significantly different between patients with inferior STEMI and those with STEMI in other regions however this is an ongoing area of controversy and focus of further research.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alteplase is a thrombolytic that is used in acute ischaemic stroke, pulmonary embolism and acute myocardial infarction."],"references":["Reed M, Kerndt CC, Nicolas D. Alteplase. [Updated 2022 Jul 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12400"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19365"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19365"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c43a5b37-341b-4d0d-92d9-27aa2cb0ac79.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c43a5b37-341b-4d0d-92d9-27aa2cb0ac79.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":413}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-27T20:12:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-27T20:12:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4908"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49317"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms